data.name: BasicCustomTraceListenerDataDescription
data.value: A class that writes log messages to a custom logging target, and is added to the Logging Application Block.

data.name: BasicCustomTraceListenerDataFilterDescription
data.value: The minimum severity of messages that will be sent to the logging target. Valid values are All (the default), Off, Critical, Error, Warning, Information, Verbose, and Activity Tracing. The behavior is for messages with the selected severity and all higher severities to be included. For example, the Warning setting will allow warning, error, and critical messages to be written to the logging target.

data.value: Listeners that do not output to a Text Formatter use this property to determine which options, or elements, should be included in the trace output. Possible values are: CallStack, DateTime, LogicalOperationStack, None, ProcessId, ThreadId, and Timestamp. The default is None. This property is optional.

data.value: The fully qualified type name of the Custom Trace Listener.

data.name: LoggingSettingsDefaultCategoryDescription
data.value: The default Logging Category to use for messages sent to the block that do not specify a Category. Categories allow log messages to be handled and processed in different ways, and sent to different logging targets. Log messages can be assigned to one or more categories.

data.name: LoggingSettingsDescription
data.value: Configuration settings for the Logging Application Block.

data.name: LoggingSettingsFormattersDescription
data.value: Configuration settings for the formatters that can be used with Listeners that generate text or binary output.

data.name: LoggingSettingsLogFiltersDescription
data.value: Filters that block or allow specific or all log messages to be written to the configured logging target based on the Category, Priority, or a custom action.

data.name: LoggingSettingsLogWarningWhenNoCategoriesMatchDescription
data.value: Specifies whether the block will write a Warning message to the logging target(s) specified in the Logging Errors and Warnings special category when a log message is received that does not match any of the defined Logging Categories.

data.name: LoggingSettingsNameDescription
data.value: Configuration settings for the Logging Application Block.

data.name: LoggingSettingsRevertImpersonationDescription
data.value: By default, log messages are written using impersonation. This provides some performance advantage for logging. This setting allows impersonation to revert to the caller.

data.name: LoggingSettingsSpecialTraceSourcesDescription
data.value: Configuration settings for built-in Categories that handle all events, events that do not match any other Category, and errors that occur when logging.

data.name: LoggingSettingsTraceListenersDescription
data.value: The Trace Listeners available to direct log messages to specific logging targets such as Windows Event Log or a database.

data.name: LoggingSettingsTraceSourcesDescription
data.value: A list of categories to which log messages can be assigned. Log messages can be assigned to one or more Categories. Each Category defines how log messages assigned that category will be handled.

data.name: LoggingSettingsTracingEnabledDescription
data.value: Specifies whether activity tracing is enabled. When enabled, code can use Tracer instances to trace individual activities and associate the resulting log messages through an Activity ID.

data.name: MsmqTraceListenerDataDescription

data.name: RollingFlatFileTraceListenerDataDescription
data.value: A logging target listener that writes log messages to a series of text files. The listener can start a new file at specified intervals, use a specified file naming pattern, and optionally overwrite existing files. Header and footer text can be specified, and the format of the message defined though a template.

data.name: RollingFlatFileTraceListenerDataFileNameDescription
data.value: The path and name of the disk file to write log message to. It can include environment variables such as %WINDIR%, %TEMP%, and %USERPROFILE%.

data.name: RollingFlatFileTraceListenerDataFilterDescription
data.value: The minimum severity of messages that will be sent to the logging target. Valid values are All (the default), Off, Critical, Error, Warning, Information, Verbose, and Activity Tracing. The behavior is for messages with the selected severity and all higher severities to be included. For example, the Warning setting will allow warning, error, and critical messages to be written to the logging target.

data.name: RollingFlatFileTraceListenerDataFooterDescription
data.value: The text of the footer to add to the log message.

data.name: RollingFlatFileTraceListenerDataFormatterDescription
data.value: The name of the Log Message Formatter to use for formatting the log message before sending it to the logging target.

data.name: RollingFlatFileTraceListenerDataHeaderDescription
data.value: The text of the header to add to the log message.

data.name: RollingFlatFileTraceListenerDataListenerDataTypeNameDescription
data.value: The fully qualified type name of the Listener.

data.name: RollingFlatFileTraceListenerDataMaxArchivedFilesDescription
data.value: The maximum number of log files to retain. When set to a numeric value, the listener will purge old files based on the file creation date when the number exceeds the specified value.

data.name: RollingFlatFileTraceListenerDataNameDescription
data.value: The name of the Rolling Flat File Trace Listener.

data.name: RollingFlatFileTraceListenerDataRollFileExistsBehaviorDescription
data.value: Determines what occurs to an existing file when it rolls over. Increment means that the listener will create a new file using a name created by incrementing the timestamp. Overwrite means that, if a value for the Timestamp Pattern is not specified, the existing file is overwritten.

data.name: RollingFlatFileTraceListenerDataRollIntervalDescription
data.value: Determines when the log file rolls over. The default is None. Other options are intervals of Midnight, Minute, Hour, Day, Month, or Year. If required, both a maximum file size and a roll interval can be specified.

data.name: RollingFlatFileTraceListenerDataRollSizeKBDescription
data.value: The maximum size of the log file, in kilobytes, before it rolls over. If required, both a maximum file size and a roll interval can be specified.

data.name: RollingFlatFileTraceListenerDataTimeStampPatternDescription
data.value: The date/time format used to create the suffix for the file name, such as 'yyyy-MM-dd'.

data.name: RollingFlatFileTraceListenerDataTraceOutputOptionsDescription
data.value: Listeners that do not output to a Text Formatter use this property to determine which options, or elements, should be included in the trace output. Possible values are: CallStack, DateTime, LogicalOperationStack, None, ProcessId, ThreadId, and Timestamp. The default is None. This property is optional.

data.name: SpecialTraceSourcesDataNotProcessedTraceSourceDescription

data.name: TraceSourceDataAutoFlushDescription
data.value: Specifies if the Logging Target Listeners will automatically flush messages to the target as soon as they are received. When set to False, the Listener buffers the messages and sends them to the target in batches or when significant events occur such as the machine shutting down.

data.name: TraceSourceDataDefaultLevelDescription
data.value: The severity level for messages that will be logged. Messages sent to the block for this category, and with a lower severity than that specified, will not be logged for this category.

data.name: TraceSourceDataDescription

data.name: TraceSourceDataNameDescription

data.name: TraceSourceDataTraceListenersDescription

data.name: XmlTraceListenerDataFileNameDescription

data.name: MsmqTraceListenerDataFormatterDescription
data.value: The formatter to use with this trace listener. This must be the Binary Formatter when you use this listener with the Message Queuing distributor service.

data.name: MsmqTraceListenerDataMessagePriorityDescription
data.value: Sets the priority of a log entry. This determines its priority while the log entry is in transit and when it is inserted into its destination queue. Possible values are: AboveNormal, High, Highest, Low, Lowest, Normal, VeryHigh, and VeryLow.

data.name: MsmqTraceListenerDataRecoverableDescription
data.value: Specifies whether the log entry is guaranteed to be delivered if there is a computer failure or network problem.

data.name: MsmqTraceListenerDataTimeToBeReceivedDescription
data.value: The total time for a log entry to be received by the destination queue.

data.name: MsmqTraceListenerDataTimeToReachQueueDescription
data.value: The maximum time for the log entry to reach the queue.

data.name: MsmqTraceListenerDataTransactionTypeDescription
data.value: The type of a Message Queuing transaction. Possible values are Automatic, None, and Single.

data.name: MsmqTraceListenerDataUseAuthenticationDescription
data.value: Specifies whether the message was (or must be) authenticated before being sent.

data.name: MsmqTraceListenerDataUseDeadLetterQueueDescription
data.value: Specifies whether a copy of a message that could not be delivered should be sent to a dead-letter queue.

data.name: MsmqTraceListenerDataUseEncryptionDescription
data.value: Specifies whether to make the message private.

data.name: MsmqTraceListenerDataQueuePathDescription
data.value: The path to the queue that the Msmq TraceListener instance uses. This attribute is a message queuing path, and it applies to the MsmqTraceListener class.

data.name: JsonLogFormatterDataDescription

data.value: The name of the JSON Log Message Formatter.

data.value: A Log Message Formatter that generates the output for a log message in a JSON text format suitable for use with listeners such as the Flat File, Rolling Flat File, Email, and Event Log Trace Listeners. Accepted values: None (Default), Indented

data.name: TraceListenerDataAsynchronousDescription
data.value: The flag indicating whether the listener should be used asynchronously.

data.name: TraceListenerDataAsynchronousDisposeTimeoutDescription
data.value: The period of time to wait for an asynchronous trace listener to finish processing buffered asynchronous requests, or infinite (expressed as "infinite").

data.name: TraceListenerDataAsynchronousBufferSizeDescription
data.value: The size of the buffer for asynchronous requests. Requests that do not fit in the buffer result in logging errors and are dropped.

data.name: TraceListenerDataAsynchronousMaxDegreeOfParallelismDescription
data.value: The maximum degree of parallelism for processing asynchronous requests for thread safe Trace Listeners. Leave empty to use the processor count.
